We recommended and Management agreed to undertake the following courses of action:
a) direct the GFPS to fully implement the GAD PPAs and monitor their implementation to ensure that optimum benefits are derived by its constituents; 
b) instruct the MPDC to facilitate the gathering of data/information needed for the creation of an updated and well-established GAD database to have an accurate and reliable basis in the planning and programming of PPAs as well as in the policy formulation in order to properly address the existing and emerging GAD issues and concerns; 
c) direct the GFPS and GAD key personnel to (i) undergo capacity building programs and training on gender and development to enhance their knowledge and build their competencies on GAD-related laws and international commitments, gender mainstreaming, gender analysis, gender-responsive planning and budgeting, and GAD-related tools like HGDG on the attributed budget to evaluate gender responsiveness of PPAs in the GBP, among others; and (ii) facilitate the establishment of the GAD Responsibility Centers to help and assist the concerned officials in the proper monitoring of the implementation of GAD related expenses and the evaluation of the effectiveness of the same.

We recommended and Management agreed to direct the:
MDRRMC to carefully plan and execute LDRRM-related PPAs to achieve the goals and objective of the fund and the desired benefits, particularly on the proper realignment of PPAs in the LDRRMIP which should be duly approved by the Local Sangggunian;
Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to (i) undertake appropriate measures and impose liquidated damages against the claims of the supplier for the delay incurred in the delivery of the ambulance; and (ii) henceforth, ensure that request for a time extension of delivery should be duly granted by the LCE based on valid and justifiable reasons;
LDRRM Officer and Municipal Accountant to (i) submit the aforementioned required documents immediately to the Office of the Auditor for proper/further evaluation of the transactions, and (ii) submit the Monthly Report on Sources and Utilization of LDRRMF within the reglementary period to COA Office for timely review of the report.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive (LCE) agreed to instruct the Municipal Accountant to:

draw adjusting entries to correct the misstatements of the PPE accounts; 


transfer of completed projects to appropriate PPE accounts; 




recognize depreciation expenses for completed Projects; and 



(iii) reclassify semi-expendable and consumable items to Inventory/Expenses; and 

henceforth, ensure that 

completed projects in the CIP accounts are reclassified to appropriate Asset accounts; 



progress billings for infrastructure projects during the year are recorded at year-end; and 

(iii) small tangible items costing below ₱15,000.00 are classified to the appropriate Inventory/Expenses accounts for accurate and fair presentation of the PPE accounts in the financial statements.

We recommended and the LCE agreed to:

instruct the Budget Officer to explain why the COVID-19 HP was paid using the appropriation intended for payment of wages of labor workers, prior to augmentation or realignment of funds; 

advise the HRMO to submit, if any, the required order authorizing the employees to physically report for work; and (ii) copy of the duties and responsibilities of the recipients during the period of grant.  Further, instruct her to explain why she failed to demand the AWA adopted by each department, monitor the reporting to office of the employees, their submission of DTRs based on the entries in the logbook of each department, and her laxity in checking the correctness and reliability of the number of days the concerned personnel reported for duty during ECQ;  

instruct the Municipal Accountant to submit the lacking DTRs/Logbook;
Accomplishment Reports of the aforementioned personnel; and (iii) to explain why some employees were able to claim more than what was allowed per DTRs and why the number of days reported for work as per payroll, DTRs and certifications issued by the Municipal Mayor/Vice Mayor/Department Heads varied; and  

advise the Immediate Supervisor of 126 employees to refund excess claims totaling ₱958,350.00.

We recommended and the LCE agreed to instruct the Municipal Accountant to 

(a) continually abide with the BIR regulation on the deadline of remittance of taxes withheld from employees as well as from suppliers/contractors; 

(b) direct the personnel in-charge to determine the exact amount to be remitted to arrive at an accurate balance of the Due to BIR at year-end; 

(c) determine the causes of over or under remittance that eventually distorted the account balance and coordinate with the BIR as regards possible offsetting of the excessive remittances against the amounts due in the succeeding remittance period; and 

(d) draw adjusting entry to adjust the Due to BIR account.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive thru the MENRO agreed to:

comply on the required composition of SWMB for proper representation thereof;

expedite the submission of the revised ten-year SWM Plan for approval of the National Solid Waste Management Commission (NSWMC);

exercise strong political will to implement the environmental laws and comply with the proper segregation, collection, and disposal of wastes;

involve closely the LGU officials and business establishments in the strict implementation of the existing environmental law and intensify information campaign towards the “no segregation, no collection policy” among the residents;

impose firmly the fines and penalties against violators of prohibited acts to improve compliance rate and provide sufficient funding for solid waste management activities;

increase the compliance rate of households and residents by educating the public through the conduct of continuous forums and seminars and placing signages and billboards in public places and in the barangay and distribution of leaflets and flyers to raise awareness; and

g) improve or construct a Materials Recovery Facility (MRF) in every barangay or, if possible, resort to clustering of MRF in small barangays with limited resources to comply with the Act.

We also reiterated our recommendation that management prioritize the repair of the Sanitary Landfill with MRF to make it operational the soonest possible time.

We recommended and management agreed to instruct the:

OIC-Municipal Engineer to: 

(i) validate substantially the reasons for the requests of suspension of works in accordance with the requirements set forth under DPWH Department Order No. 156, s. 2015; 

(ii) indicate the number of days of suspension before recommending the approval of the suspension orders; 


(iii) monitor closely the physical accomplishment of the projects and check for possible imposition of liquidated damages due to delayed implementation; and 

(iv) ensure that the accomplishments indicated in the Statement of Work Accomplished (SWA) prepared by the contractor matched with the actual accomplishments to date; and

Municipal Accountant, in coordination with the OIC-Municipal Engineer and BAC Secretariat to: 

(i) submit the certified copy of Project Logbook on the two infrastructure projects in accordance with DPWH Department Order No. 216 dated November 16, 2000; 

(ii) require the contractor to post performance security valid until the issuance of the Certificate of Final Acceptance by the Agency; and 

(iii) ensure that all disbursement vouchers are properly supported with complete documentation before making any payment.

We recommended and the Head of the Procuring Entity (HoPE) agreed to instruct the:

Bids and Awards Committee, together with its TWG and Secretariat to:

comply with the required period in posting the Notice of Award;

require interested contractors to submit DOLE-approved CSHP to ensure the latter’s compliance with Occupational Safety and Health Standards set by the DOLE; 

comply with Sections 39 and 62 of the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 requiring the contractor to post performance security with validity until the issuance of the Certificate of Final Acceptance and warranty security which runs for a period of one year from the date of final acceptance of the project; and

scrutinize thoroughly the documents submitted by the bidders to ensure their authenticity, veracity, and completeness as basis for the evaluation of the most advantageous and reasonable bids.

Municipal Accountant, in coordination with the OIC-Municipal Engineer and BAC Secretariat, to: 

(i) 	submit the lacking documents mentioned above; 

(ii)	verify all supporting documents as to completeness and see to it that the same are attached to the disbursement vouchers before payments are made to establish the legality and proper accountability over financial transactions; and

(iii)	adhere to the withholding of ten percent (10%) retention money on progress payments to contractor to cover possible uncorrected discovered defects and third-party liabilities.

OIC - Municipal Engineer to:

(i)	integrate the Construction Safety and Health Program in the computation of construction costs of all projects to be implemented by the Municipality to ensure utmost protection and welfare of the workers at the construction site as well as the general public passing within its vicinity;

(ii)	 submit the basis of computation of the ABC; 

(iii)	consider the adoption of DPWH Department Order No. 197, series of 2016 dated October 07, 2016 on the Revised Guidelines in the Preparation of Approved Budget for the Contract (ABC), to the extent possible; and

(iv)	submit written explanation on the noted (a) excessive labor cost for first aider and safety practitioner; and (b) variance on the computation of ABC and supporting Program of Works and Detailed Unit Price Analysis (DUPA).

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to consider the following measures:

a)	instruct the Municipal Accountant to: 

draw Journal Entry Vouchers (JEVs) taking up the issued/consumed supplies and materials at year-end and reclassification of procured laptop and printer from Office Supplies Expenses to Information and Communication Technology Equipment;







record the purchases under the proper Inventories account; and 




(iii) maintain supplies ledger cards for all inventory accounts to support the recorded balances of inventory;

b)	require the Municipal Treasury and/or Supply Officer to: 

(i) prepare the stock cards for the purchased supplies; 



conduct periodic inventory of supplies as prescribed by the above regulation; 




prepare the corresponding Report on the Physical Count of Inventories and submit the same to the Accounting Office for reconciliation with the reported inventory balances in the books; 
(iv) prepare and submit to the Accounting Office the Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI) monthly for issued inventories based on actual consumption/issuance for accurate recording of expenses and assets accounts for the period; 
