instruct the Municipal Budget Officer to ensure that the 20% Development Fund is exclusively utilized to finance programs and projects which are in the nature of investment or capital expenditures in accordance with DILG-DBM Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2011-1 dated April 13, 2011;
instruct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that all disbursement vouchers are properly supported with complete documentation to facilitate validation of the regularity and propriety of the claims; otherwise, those disbursement claims noted to be irregular and improper shall be disallowed in audit; and
consider revisiting the contracts that have not been pursued or partially implemented during the year 2016 and re-appropriate the same in the ensuing year for their completion.  Evaluate the extent of non-compliance of contractors with existing contracts and enforce sanctions against defective workmanship, excessive payments to contractors if any, and other violations of the provisions stipulated in the contract.

We recommended that the management:
prohibit the open burning of solid wastes like hay stalks, dried leaves and other farm wastes to protect air and water from pollution; prioritize the repair of the damaged portion of the Sanitary Landfill to make it operational the soonest possible time;ensure that waste collectors and segregators are equipped with personal protective equipment to free them from hazards of handling solid wastes;
exert more effort to claim warranty from the supplier for the repair of garbage compactor to speed up the collection, transport and disposal of solid wastes;
encourage the active participation of schools, private organizations and the barangay officials in informing and educating households in the proper waste disposal from source; and
coordinate with the barangay officials for the establishment and operation of Materials Recovery Facility (MRF) within their respective barangay and adhere to the rules and regulations provided under Sections 32 of RA No. 9003.

We recommended that the management:
maximize the utilization of LDRRMF to ensure the smooth delivery of calamity-related programs, projects and activities. Likewise, consider the procurement of early warning systems, preparedness equipment and other equipage for floods, earthquake, volcanic eruptions, landslide and other natural and man-made calamities out of the 70% Mitigation Fund;
refrain from using the LDRRMF for non-disaster related activities;
instruct the Municipal Accountant to perform a thorough review of all disbursement claims to make sure that these are properly supported with complete documentation;
advise the Municipal Budget Officer to (i) guard against overlapping of funds in the budget by maintaining complete registry for each expense class, such as RAAO-for QRF; RAAO-for MOOE; and RAAO for CO; and (ii) include any unexpended balance of DRRMF-CO in the continuing balance under the General Fund until the projects are completed.  In such manner, proper monitoring of funds may be ensured and the correct balance of savings for transfer to the Special Trust Fund may be established in accordance with COA Circular No. 2012-002, dated September 12, 2012; and
instruct the Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator (MPDC) to provide in the LDRRMFIP a separate list of programs, projects and activities to be undertaken out of the unexpended LDRRMF of previous years.

11.17	We recommended that the:
Members of the SB consider enacting appropriate ordinance on the regulation of the operations of three-wheeled public conveyances to prevent undesirable outcomes as a result of unregulated proliferation of tricycles along the national highways, which may pose hazards and imminent danger to pedestrians and motorists’ lives and properties and impede the flow of traffic;
Municipal Human Resource Officer consider the necessity of hiring traffic enforcers that would apprehend and impose fines and penalties to traffic violators;
consider enacting an ordinance regulating the issuance of franchise and other fees on tricycle operation in the Municipality; and
Provide funding for the installation of Closed Circuit Televisions (CCTVs) to monitor the situation in the locality including safety and traffic conditions in major thoroughfares within the Municipality; facilitate tracking and investigation of violators; and provide legislators (SB) with situational updates for improving existing ordinances.

We recommended that management adopt the following courses of action:

require the public health workers and public social workers to secure and submit the certification/proof from the LCE that they were exposed to either high/low risk hazards/hazardous areas and handling occupational risks respectively;



establish a procedure for identifying personnel who shall be exposed to high/low risk hazard and occupational risks including the duration of such exposure based on the list of position with job descriptions/actual duties. This will be forwarded to the LCE to serve as guide for his issuance of certification;

compute the hazard allowance of PSW equivalent to 20% of their basic salary while PHW based on the degree of exposure to hazard areas whether high of low risk pursuant to DBM and DOH Joint Circular No. 1, Series of 2012 dated November 29, 2012.



deduct from hazard allowance of public social worker the amount corresponding to the number of days employees were on official travel, leave and absent;



cause the refund by the concerned employees the amount of ₱35,157.35 representing overpayment of claims for hazard pay.

